    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-02-04T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-02-04T16:00:00-05:00" n="73"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d73">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">883.00/1236: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-02-04T23:00:00+02:00"
                            >February 4, 1942—11 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 11:16 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>198. My 197, February 4, 7 p.m. Following the surrounding of the Palace by
                    British troops the British Ambassador accompanied by the general officer
                    commanding British troops in Egypt and a strong escort called at the Palace at 9
                    o’clock tonight and after delivering a prepared statement presented a letter of
                    abdication for the King’s signature. The King thereupon made a plea for leniency
                    and immediately called in Nahas Pasha to form a new government. At present
                    writing Nahas is in conference with the British Ambassador and it is not yet
                    known what type of government he intends forming.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
